export const content = `
If You Had Infinite Resources, What Would You Do?

Take a second with that question. Don't answer too fast.

If money, time, obligation, all of it disappeared tomorrow, what would you actually do with your life?
If your mind went blank just now, you're not alone. Most of us can't answer it. Most of us spent so long running, toward the next deadline, the next milestone, the next thing that looks like safety...that we forgot to ask where we actually want to end up.

I've been in that fog for a while. Years of making decisions based on what seemed responsible, what wouldn't blow up in my face. Burnout crept in quietly as the exhaustion of optimizing hard for goals I never consciously chose. I was always afraid of making the wrong move. 

Somewhere in between, a professor I grab coffee with dropped the infinite resource question to me. It was precise question. He's a researcher who thinks in trajectories and objective functions, and he has just offered me a guideline for finding our own objective function, before we waste years optimizing for someone else's.

We covered many things in that conversation, so let me just share the parts I keep coming back to.

## Our past is a sample, not a sentence
Let's look at how optimization actually works. You're an agent walking through a high-dimensional space you can't fully see. The environment is vast, it's dark, and it's constantly shifting. You take a step, you get some signal, and you update. That's all you can do, and that's the real world. 

The people around us, our parents, our families, they were agents too, walking through their own version of that space. But the environment they navigated was different. The timing was different. Even if we put the same agent in the same environment at the same moment, the outcome isn't guaranteed. Flip a coin. Same coin, same hand, same force, we still get heads sometimes and tails others. That's all just probability.

So the experiences that shaped us, the hardship, the family dynamics, the weight of watching people we love struggle...those are data points. Real ones, meaningful ones. But they are a handful of samples from one slice of an environment that no longer exists. They don't define the full distribution of what's possible for us.
Collect more data. Walk further into the space. Don't let a few early samples write the rest of the trajectory.

## Humans have bandwidth. Accept it
He said it plainly: we have limits, and pretending otherwise doesn't expand them, it just burns them down. Rest isn't a reward for finishing. It's a requirement for functioning. We cannot run a good algorithm on a broken machine. (I really needed to hear this.)

## There is no "finding yourself."
The idea that there's some true self buried underneath everything, some core you need to excavate and return to, he doesn't buy it. People are adaptive. We change, we grow, we contradict ourselves. There's no fixed center to find. The supposed true self is not "discovered", however build brick by brick, habit by habit, by ourselves. 

## Know your objective before you start optimizing.
Now you're looking forward. Asssume you're rested, you're not trapped by your past, you're not waiting for some revelation. So what do you *actually* want?

Many times, we jump straight to the how — the grind, the plan, the execution — without ever clearly defining the what. And if we don't know what we're solving for, every optimization is just noise. We can work incredibly hard and move in exactly the wrong direction.

So reader, you may ask, now how did you, the author, answer those questions? 

I had been running on empty for a while without really admitting it to myself. Five, six years of drifting and grinding, never once stopping. It wasn't until he asked me that question that I realized, oh, this is what burnt out actually feels like. I decided to take a rather long break and see what will happen; turned out it only took 3 months to rest from the 5 years turmoil for my hands to get itchy and start building cool websites again. This time with a cleansed and calm mind.

About the infinite resource question, my first answer was to be with my oversea grandparents. More time, more presence, before that window closes. Second, I want to travel and draw manga. It has been my lifelong dream to see the world, to document it in my own way, and to present such curiosity that adds color to my life to inpsire other. 

At the same time, I feel like I should be doing something even more useful. There are people suffering. Who am I to spend my life drawing?

He didn't dismiss that. But I think the point is that guilt is also data. It's telling me something real about what I value. And yet it can also be another form of the same trap: optimizing for what looks responsible, what looks selfless, instead of what's actually mine.

I don't have a clean resolution to the tension. I'm not sure I should. Maybe the most honest thing is to hold both, the desire to make something beautiful, and the awareness that not everyone gets to ask this question freely. That privilege is real. It's worth naming.

I'm writing this not because I have it figured out. I don't. But sitting with this question gave me a direction to face, even if I don't have every step mapped out.
So I'll leave you where he left me.

If you had infinite resources — time, money, freedom, all of it — what would you do?
Don't answer too fast. It's a harder question than it sounds. And it might be the most important one you ask yourself.

*Thanks to Professor Gao Sicun for chatting with me! Long live the nearest neighbors.*
`